---
title: Jammy Bacon & Gouda Melts with Caramelized Onion & Sweet Potato Wedges
description: Yes, we’re calling this dish a “melt” but let’s get real: It’s a spectacularly flavorful grilled cheese. Are we too old for that? NEVER! You’ll layer sourdough with gouda, Monterey Jack, caramelized onion, and bacon, plus a luscious smear of fig jam for a sweet contrast. Pan-fry them in butter until golden brown and melty and serve with roasted sweet potatoes on the side (because we are adults and we love our vitamins).
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/jammy-bacon-gouda-melts-cc06d978.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/jammy-bacon-gouda-melts-63b47aac5574be2c5b0b5732-530172a3.pdf
course: main course
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/jammy-bacon-gouda-melts-63b47aac5574be2c5b0b5732
servings: 2
author: Sara Heilman
time required: 35 minutes
cuisine: North America
nutrition:
  calories: 1060 kcal
  fat: 61 g
  saturated fat: 28 g
  carbohydrates: 105 g
  sugar: 23 g
  protein: 30 g
  fiber: 8 g
  sodium: 1730 mg
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Heat a large dry pan over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce}; cook, turning
occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy,
~{6-10%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a paper-towel-lined #plate{}. Carefully
discard all but 1 tsp bacon fat (2 tsp for 4 servings) from pan. (You'll use this to
cook the onion later.)

While bacon cooks, cut @sweet potatoes{2} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Halve, peel,
and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}.

Toss sweet potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon},
@salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until golden brown,
~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, add a drizzle of oil to pan with reserved bacon fat; heat over
medium-high heat. Add onion; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and
softened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Add half the @fig jam{1}% (you'll use the rest later),
¼ cup water (½ cup for 4 servings), and @sugar{1%teaspoon} (2 tsp for 4); cook,
stirring occasionally, until onion is caramelized and jammy, ~{2-3%minutes} more.
Season with salt and pepper.

Turn off heat; transfer to a plate. Wash out pan.

Top half the @sourdough bread{4%slice} with even layers of @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup}
and caramelized onion; drizzle with remaining jam. Arrange bacon and
@gouda cheese{4%slice} on top.

> TIP: If gouda slices don't fit, cut them in half and shingle on sandwiches.

Close sandwiches with remaining sourdough slices.

Melt 1 TBSP @butter{2%tablespoon} in pan used for onion over medium heat. Add
sandwiches and cook, pushing them around pan to absorb butter, until bread is
golden brown on one side and cheese begins to melt, ~{4-6%minutes}. Add another
1 TBSP butter to pan and flip; cook until bread is golden brown on second side and
cheese melts.

> For 4 servings, work in batches or use a second pan, adding 1 TBSP butter for
> each side.

Halve melts on a diagonal.

Divide melts between #plates{} and serve with sweet potato wedges on the side.

> Bacon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.